472–Deceased","1474–1504":"1474–1504","1500–1591":"1500–1591","1389–Male":"1389–Deceased","1400–1446":"1400–1446","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","       1472":"1472","1591":"1591","       1414":"1414","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1400":"1400","1389":"1389","1520":"1520","1474":"1474","about 1500":"about 1500","1518":"1518","about 1471":"about 1471","1504":"1504","1438":"1438","Of Benenden,Kent,Eng":"Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Louth, County Louth, Ireland":"Louth, County Louth, Ireland","England":"England","Kent,Eng":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Benchley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name apparently from Beckley in Sussex, which is no doubt also one of the sources of the surname   Beckley  . Beckley is named with the Old English personal name <i>Becca</i> + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The development of [k] to [tʃ] is seen in some of the early forms of the placename. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Variant of   Beeghly   or   Beighley  , surnames of German origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Beckley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so named in Oxfordshire and Sussex, from the Old English byname <i>Becca</i> (see   Beck   3) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: variant of   Bickley  .","Americanized form of South German <b>Bächle</b> (see   Baechle  ) and of its Swiss German cognate <b>Bächli</b>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Catherine Benchley Benenden was born in 1450, in Benenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom, her father, Lord John Brenchley, was 61 and her mother, Margaret Golding, was 50. She married Thomas William Moore about 1471, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1518, in her hometown, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1450–1518":"1450–1518","1438–1520":"1438–1520","1472–Male":"1472–Surnud","1474–1504":"1474–1504","1500–1591":"1500–1591","1389–Male":"1389–Surnud","1400–1446":"1400–1446","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","       1472":"1472","1591":"1591","       1414":"1414","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1400":"1400","1389":"1389","1520":"1520","1474":"1474","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1518":"1518","about 1471":"umbes 1471","1504":"1504","1438":"1438","Of Benenden,Kent,Eng":"Benenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Louth, County Louth, Ireland":"Louth, County Louth, Iirimaa","England":"England","Kent,Eng":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England, United Kin